Notes: Open cluster in Auriga. Gray area was elusive, only visible with averted vision
Very faint--have to use averted vision to see anything but the core.  M32 looks like a star
Much brighter than in binoculars - this part of the sky is pretty bright because of the moon and a football game.
A: bigger, light orange. B: smaller, light blue.
Seems like a spiral of stars going in; faintest hint of nebulosity in the center (Didn't know about the name until after writing this description!)
Can barely make out a ring with averted vision -- else just a light blur.
Nice triangular-shaped open cluster. Stars are very crisp and clear and bright.
Very faint, with averted vision seems like a speckle of stars.
Looks like 73 to me.
Primary is a light orange. Secondary is blue (rather deep blue for a star); much fainter. Nice double!
White/pale blue. Looks like a big star, but not as bright.
Supposedly a triple star.  Yes, in finderscope this appears as 3 stars clumped together. :)
Double star. Secondary is very faint, just outside the bright sparkle of the primary. Can see hints of the diffractions patterns due to the spider.
Kind of a pear shape of faint nebulosity - slightly sparkly.
Can see separation between primary and secondary, but lots of noise around the stars. This is a 6-star system, I believe.
No nebulosity, but very sharp, bright stars.
Can't tell which of the close pair is primary; equal brightness. Both are white. Note: if I had better luck and a higher magnification, should be a triple star.
Smaller than I expected. Lots more stars (not shown) with averted vision. General pentagon shape. Shaded ovals show areas with many smaller dimmer stars.
Light orange color. Really stands out.
Two brighter stars in a cluster, then sort of a hexagonal grid. Then grayer area that resolves to lots of faint stars with averted vision.
Nebulosity is brightest near the trapezium (see 4 stars) and the row of 3. Also some about the star farther down (M43). Very pretty.
Looks like a Christmas tree!
Double. Both appear pale orange.
Both appear bright orange. Nicely separated.
Bright core, with averted vision, a hint of resolving some stars. Seems generally rather gray.
Both bright white.
Bright white disk. Can see 2 main bands and 2 fainter ones at the top and bottom. Closest moon seems to have moved farther from Jupiter after 15 min.
Found this pretty fast today - aimed the red dot finder where I thought it would be, and there it was in the scope!
Very cool - I like the two pairs of doubles in the view. :)
A: white, maybe a hint of blue. B: very pale orange. Pretty double, tricky to find in LP skies.
Both stars are white. Easily split even at 30x.
Hints of more (much fainter) stars with averted vision. Stars are well spread out.
Lots of nebulosity around the primary. Secondary is faint but distinct pin prick.
Lots of very bright white stars. Fairly spread out.
Just a white dot. Other stars for reference. A: 66 CnC, B: 63 CnC
All stars are white, approx same brightness. Sky is washed out here, so contrast could be better. Somewhat faint.
No color in stars.
Beautiful heart-shaped open cluster. Seems to have a small concentration of stars in center right.
Lots of bright stars. I would name this the "Yoshi Cluster". Can easily be seen in 9x50 finderscope.
Primary is yellow, secondary appears dim orange
Looks like an upside down palm tree.
Looks like 71 to me. Lighter stars drawn here are only visible with averted vision.
Long and thin, just a fuzz, no more detail. A little larger, wider with averted vision.
Center much brighter than the rest, although entire galaxy disappears without averted vision.
Brighter in the center. Can't resolve any stars. Whole thing is fairly bright. No averted vision needed.
Looks like a hexagon with a heart on top. Many more stars not drawn.
Concentrated stars at the center. Almost seems like a hint of nebulosity. One bright star.

A: M66 - seems the brightest. Bright core, roundish. B: M65 - slightly dimmer and more eccentric. Also bright core. C: NGC 3628 - looks edge-on. Much fainter, only visible with averted vision. No core.
Clearly two galaxies, with brighter cores.  Appear face-on. Slight separation between them. Hint that they may be connected at the top.
Nice snake-shaped sequence of stars in the center.
Very large, spread out cluster. Stars all very bright.
Some concentrations of very faint stars.
Somewhere between a C and a 3. :)
No strong concentration. General pentagon shape. Relatively faint stars.
All stars are white. Nice triple! Second and third stars seem equal in brightness. Cleanly split.
Circular. Brighter center. Looks like a star at lower magnification. Took four attempts to find this!
Looks like an inchworm. Direction a little hard to determine accurately since near zenith and scope is slipping a little.
Nice little globular cluster. Can't resolve any stars. Center is brighter.
Looks like a nice hat. Stars were relatively faint.
Both stars are white. Secondary is fainter, just a pinpoint of light.
Both stars are white. Compared to iota Bootes, these are a little closer, and secondary is brighter.
Can see the coathanger with some effort. Stars are not the same brightness; some on the handle require averted vision to see.

Drawn slightly larger than actually appears in the view. Two bands are obvious, a third, polar band is visible for certain instants of time. Bands are light brown. Supposedly should see the shadow of Io, but no luck.
Very bright, can't use high power since telescope not cooled. Can see that it's gibbous.
Very large and bright. Generally spherical, but appears to have a few chains of stars coming out on the sides.
Doubles not cleanly split, especially epsilon1. However can see two pinpricks for epsilon2.
Quick sketch of the edge of the moon as it was getting covered by a cloud. A: Anaxagoras; B: Epigenes, C: Birmingham
Primary star looks a little yellower and secondary is whiter. Easily split. Could see two points with a 25mm eyepiece.
Two great bands. Can see some variability in thickness of the biggest one. Higher band seems broken into two spots.
Moon closest to Jupiter has been moving up and away (SW). Can see 3 bands clearly, hints of a fourth.
No detail, just a white gibbous disc. Can see some chromatic aberration -- top is red, bottom is violet.
Just a gray patch, slightly brighter in the center
Surprisingly clear, given that I was looking through a cloud! Can see two large bands, bottom band looks darker, and another faint band near the top.
Secondary star is easily separated, but much dimmer. Compass directions are approximate based on the location of the diamond ring in the finderscope.
Moons 1,4 are the brightest, 3 next, 4 is dimmest. All perfectly in a line. Can see different darknesses within the bands.
Small cluster of 7 brighter stars, with a few more dim ones. Not much concentration, rather sparse. Other stars outside this view are much brighter.
Nice clear gibbous shape. Can see the dark side in shadow.
Jupiter visible through the clouds, bands still visible.
Nice bright stars. All white. Classic.
LP is bad enough that this is just a fuzzy with direct vision. But averted vision gives lots of stars and detail. Amazing!
(Compared to M 5) Much fainter. Stars seem more distinct, not as dense.
Fairly bright ring. Inside the ring might be slightly brighter than outside.
Super bright! Can see two main bands and part of a third.
Beige color. Outside of rings are darker. Hint of the Cassini division.
M23 - Loose stars, not really any brighter in the center. Vesta - bright (brighter than the rest of the stars), slightly yellow color. Easily seen in the 9x50 finderscope, but not naked eye.
Can see darker shades (twilight?) towards the edge of the lit side.
Somewhat dim. Fairly large. Easy to see lots of stars. Center is brighter, seems like a line of stars through the center.
Quite faint. Mostly need averted vision to see anything. Slightly brighter core. Can resolve some stars.

Wow. This is like the Pleiades -- lots of bright stars scattered, no concentration. Need bigger FOV to fully take this in! Only brighter stars drawn here. Background looks like the milky way through binoculars.
Small globular. Can't resolve any stars. Brighter in the center.
Very big, bright. Can resolve lots of stars. Surrounded by a nice ring of stars. Lots more fainter stars, but covered in a cloud before could fill in a more detailed sketch.
Nice open cluster of stars. Lots of nebulosity, esp in binoculars. Was going to pack things up until I saw this.
Drawn larger.  Can see the terminator is a shade darker than the lit side.
Very bright. Outer part of rings are dimmer. Almost seems like a belt across saturn. Can see the shadow of the rings on Saturn.  T: Titan. R: Rhea. I: Iapetus
Crips open cluster. Seems to have a small concentration of stars in the bottom middle of the "W"
Hard to tell where the boundary of this cluster is. Nice pentagon in the middle. Curious if there would be lots more stars in a darker sky; I don't see many really faint ones.
Slight concentration of stars near the center.
Quite bright; core is the brightest. Can't resolve any stars distinctly, but it has a speckled appearance. With averted vision.  Can see some stars at the edge.
Super bright orange. Very large. Not much detail.  Can see a whiter area on the N pole and a slightly darker area towards the south.

A: visually looks like it might be a planetary nebula. Seems brighter and with averted vision sometimes see a small disc around it.  B: position seems more correct, but looks sharper, more star-like. [Yes, confirmed with Stellarium that A is the PN.]
Lots of stars. No concentration. Very pretty. :)
Very spread out; stars have very different magnitudes
Lots of fairly faint stars -- too many to draw accurately. At lower powers this looks like a faint globular.
Very dim. Stars resolve with averted vision, with direct vision it's just a lighter gray patch
Very faint gray patch. Hint of some stars with averted vision.  Have to shake the telescope to find this. Slight brighter in the core.
Mostly just a faint smudge. Can see hints of stars with averted vision.
Very small, bright core. However with averted vision can see it's quite large and diffuse at the edges. I like this one! :)
Both stars are bright white. Primary is quite bright. Easy split.
Brighter core. Only the faintest hint of any stars with averted vision; mostly a smudge.
Nice open cluster; a few bright stars and many very faint ones. Some slight nebulosity visible next to the star on the left.  Not as impressive as at the darker site, but still pretty cool.
Very open cluster. Not too many stars.
Looks mostly like an open cluster. Possibly the faintest hint of nebulosity around the double star ear the center; the area is just slightly brighter.
Very faint. Core is not much brighter than the edges. Can see some stars with averted vision. Many faint stars everywhere in the field; too many to sketch
Modestly bright blurry patch. A bit squarish with a piece taken out on the side. Very nice. :)
Very faint blur. Can't resolve any stars. hard to see, even after aiming right at it.
Nice geometric patterns white stars well-spaced.
Very small crescent. Very blurry. Can only be seen with the telescope; can't even see with 10x50 finder. Mercury is close to the moon tonight. I used that to locate it.
Saturn is blurry and swimming. Fairly yellow
Mostly a faint smudge. Center is a little brighter. Can't resolve any stars.
Nice triangular pattern. "Triangle cluster?"
Lots of stars, but most are very dim.  Faint, almost nebulous, with averted vision.
Very faint; can barely see without averted vision. Just a slightly lighter patch.
Large, not very bright. Can see hints of some stars; speckled with averted vision. Yikes (to the transparency and light pollution).
Nice bright triangle of stars on the east. Other stars are fairly faint. No central core of stars.

Round and fuzzy, bright in the middle. Does get dimmer when I look straight at it. With 8mm EP, this was even more striking, where it would almost completely disappear with straight vision and get very bright with averted vision. Very cool. :)
Fairly large. Faint. Slightly brighter in the center. Hints of stars with averted vision.
Hints of nebulosity? or just a little brighter around the bright stars in the middle.
Extremely faint. Almost disappears with direct vision. Appear to have some stars there too.  Slightly lighter blur.
Modestly bright blur.  "Discovered" by accident.
Fuzzy patch with bright core. Extends fairly large with averted vision. Only had a few (30?) seconds to see it before clouds covered it.
Cluster at the bottom reminds me of a little eiffel tower.
Hints of more faint stars within the quadrilateral, esp. near the right point, but only have vague glimpses of them.
Spectacular! Stars look like 2 piles of diamonds. NGC 884 (right) looks a bit like a ring, where NGC 864 like a very sparse, fully split globular.
Faint. Stars are all widely separated.
M31 has very bright core but seems to spread out very faintly. M32 is a small fuzzy; starlike with direct vision. M110 is not visible.
Could easily see two bands, but not time to look very closely as it set behind some trees.

Not too much detail. Can see big gaps between side of Saturn and the rings, and a fain dark gap on the outer part of the rings. Nice shadow on the side of the planet. Some chromatic aberration as indicated.
Inside of crater is slightly lighter than the surrounding area.

Generally, Tycho is white, but there's a brighter white ring on the inside, with slightly darker interior. Outside crater is darker, gradually lightening the farther out you go. White dot in the middle. Lunar rays are white.
Byrgius A is bright white. Lunar rays surrounding are light gray, and surrounding area is medium gray.
Small. Craters have a faint light border on shadow side (hard to draw) and darker border on the light side.
Very white walls on inside; look vertical. Tiny bump in the middle. Generally very circular, just a small break in the walls near Cameron crater.
Sinus Concordiae is triangular shaped, bordering the Sea of Tranquility. Most prominent points are Cauchy crater and the mountain marked by the *.
Moderately faint, uneven open star cluster. Almost nebulous, need better skies/aperture to resolve.
Faint smudge. Core is brighter than the sides. Can't resolve any stars.

With direct vision, looks like one star; with slight averted vision looks like a blur, which is why I'm pretty sure this is a Messier object. With more averted vision can see 3 stars, can't see if there are any more.
See a very faint blur near M 31. Suspect it may be M 110. Very soft, looks taller than wide. Maybe slightly brighter in the core.  The large glow of M 31 is visible in the south of the view.
Saturn looks very 3D today. Appears to have a light band. A: Titan; very bright about 4 Saturns away. B: a star; next brightest, with averted vision. C: Rhea; right at the edge of detectability.
Lots of stars, many different magnitudes. Very open, no single point of concentration.
Long thin cluster. Many stars are just visible with averted vision. Area in center looks like it has hundreds of stars.
Small and somewhat faint globular cluster. Just a blur, with slightly brighter center
Fairly bright globular cluster. With averted vision texture is speckled with stars.
Just a bright ellipse, no real separation between planet and rings.  Though with close inspection, can just make out hints between planet and rings.  The dot nearest to Saturn is Titan.
Primary looks yellow, secondary whiter. Cleanly separated
All star very faint, but there are lots. Almost all are difficult to see with direct vision. Would call this the "Dreamcatcher Cluster". More stars concentrated in the lightly shaded area.
Round, white, concentrated blur. Maybe not as soft as a globular. Slightly brighter in the center.
Very beautiful. Lots of bright white stars. Also looks good at 25mm (30x). Almost a cluster in a cluster
Golf putter star are bright pinpricks. NGC 752 is rather dim, but stars still resolvable without averted vision.
Faint white dot. Not color, looks like a star
Bright and has a yellow tint. Other stars white
Rather bare cluster; not too many stars. Looks like a crab claw grabbing for the bright star.
Looks like an airplane, or a martini glass, or a bat. Worth looking at again. :)
Fairly open cluster, not too memorable except that it looks like it has a happy face hidden in it.
Most stars here are very faint.
Fairly bright globular, could see in the finderscope. Can't resolve any stars. Appears smooth and fuzzy.
Primary is light yellow. Secondary is gray-blue. Nice colors!
Open cluster with just a few stars.
Nice cluster. Lots of bright white stars. Slightly more concentrated in the center.
Very faint. At this magnification, see some speckling with averted vision.
Very faint globular. See a brighter point in the middle, like a fuzzy star, then hints of other stars nearby.
Looks pretty big, but rather dim. Can see some speckling of stars. Core is not particularly bright.
Both bright white. Wide, easy split, could split in finder.
Both white. Primary is much brighter than secondary.
A: primary, light orange. B: secondary, light blue. Not as vibrant as Albireo, but still very nice. Easily split (faintly even in the finder).
Both are very nearly the same magnitude and have a light orange color. A: primary; B: secondary. I get the name - stars are in a pizza shaped circle.
Easily split here, but tight to draw. Primary is light yellow, secondary is white.
A: light orange. B: slightly lighter orange. C: white. D: white, much fainter. A = O1 Cyg = 31 Cyg, B = O2 Cyg = 32 cyg, C = 30 Cyg
Looks like a set of three soap bubbles.
Both stars are white, roughly equal in magnitude. Bright star in the West is 70 UMa
Grimaldi looks smooth and darker -- like a Mare. Around it are small white craterlets and rough mountains. Basin is slightly darker near the top, but has two lighter streaks on it.
Cruger: small, very circular. Smoother darker gray. Nearby is slightly lighter Lacus Aestatis, and a white/dark spot
Stars are close but clearly separated. Very sharp. Primary looks golden and secondary is bluish. Nice!
A: white. B: pale yellow, has a faint double. C: pale yellow. D: white
Primary is bright orange; secondary is dimmer, gray-blue
Both stars are white. However, A is a light orange and B is a deeper orange.
Both stars are white and about equally bright. Guess that A may be the primary. Prominent "broken ring" asterism.
Long line of stars in this cluster, and a little bit of a hat shape.
Both stars are white. Primary is much brighter than secondary.
Primary is somewhat brighter than secondary. Primary is white, secondary seems brick red when defocused or using averted vision. Straight on it looks white.
Nice triple. All stars are white. Secondary and tertiary are about the same magnitude.
Primary has a yellow tint and is quite bright. Secondary is white. Also there's a distinctive arrowhead asterism in the view. :)
Both stars have approx the same magnitude. Not a perfectly clean split, but can see two distinct stars touching.
Both white. A is slightly brighter than B.
Primary has a strong yellow tint, secondary also looks a little yellowish. Big star hop to get here from Fomalhaut, the closest visible star naked eye.
Extremely bright white spot, small. Nearby is light gray, farther is darker gray in mare Tranquilitatis

Hercules looks like a large deep crater. Hercules G is very bright and sharp inside. Hercules E is very small, mostly hidden in shadow. Can just see the general shape of it. Atlas has two mountains/peaks in the center.
Small, almost star-like, but slightly fuzzy.
Small and a little fuzzy. Center is bright, but doesn't look like a star.
Primary is white and secondary appears blue. Barely separated.
I'll call this the snail cluster. Relatively dim. Seems like some nebulosity with direct vision, but averted vision just shows stars.
Nice rectangle in the middle with a double star inside. Quite a few bright stars.
Stars are about equal brightness, and are white. Very clean split.
Wide double. Primary has a faint yellow color. Secondary seems white.
Rather blind movements through finderscope to get this.  Roughly equal magnitudes, but A is the primary B the secondary. Both are white.
Fairly tight double, but cleanly split. Equal magnitudes, both are white.
Looks like a star. No color.  At 5mm, Neptune appears blurry, and Triton barely seen with averted vision as a pinprick.
Modestly large, very very faint -- can only see with averted vision. Jiggling the scope helps. Shape is amorphous, but doesn't seem exactly circular. One are does seem to be a bit brighter.
Primary is yellow-orange. Secondary is rather dimmer and blue-white. Fairly close split.
Primary is bright, white-orange. Secondary is much dimmer and bluish. Could split at 30x, but seconary was so dim it was hard to distinguish from the diffraction spikes/aberrations of the primary.
Both stars are bright white. Primary is much brighter than the secondary. Easy split.
Extremely dim, rather large circular blur. Can only see occasionally with averted vision. Core is slightly brighter. Roughly centered in a nice rhombus of stars.
Both stars are white and the primary is only a little brighter than the secondary. Star hopping here is a pain.
Not very cleanly split. Stars are white, primary very slightly brighter.
Bright, gibbous phase. In the center Mars is a bit darker/grayer. Rest is a pale orange. Terminator is slightly dimmer.
Primary is bright white-orange. Assume secondary is the next brightest star, is much dimmer and blue.
Somewhat dim, spread out open cluster. Looks like a sideways goblet.
One of my favorite binocular open clusters. Have fond memories of the first time I saw this. Glittery bright white stars, very bright.
A mini version of Delphinus the dolphin!
Long strand of stars all in a straight line. Can see more here than with binoculars since the view is steady.
A faint blur, easiest seen with averted vision. Center is brighter, and fades off to a fairly large area.
Looks like a fuzzy star. Fairly circular.
Large faint disc, slightly brighter in the middle. Circular. Not so hard to see tonight.
Somewhat irregular shape, roughly evenly bright, though a little fainter near the edge.
Very recognizable as a baseball home plate. Two stars are really doubles.
Right at zenith, so very uncomfortable to find. Had to kneel on my toes.  Nice 7 shape. Almost seems like a wide open cluster.
Very bright. Stars are all white. Lots of little chains of stars.
Very open and bright. Aldeberan is bright orange. Need lower magnification to get the whole cluster.
Stars are all colorful and twinkly. Can see a little nebulosity at M42. Nice view
Lots of very sharp detail at the terminator. Can make out tons of craters, seas, and lunar rays. Dark side is slightly lighter than the sky.

Rupes Recta (straight wall) is a very prominent vertical line, fairly straight and dark. Thebit has a very dark edge on one side, light on the other. Looks deep. Thebit A looks deep but smaller (bowl-shaped?) Thebit L is very small - just a dot.
Delaunay looks like it's cloven in two with a hill/mountain across the middle. Top half is dark gray to gray, and the bottom is gray to light gray.
Primary and secondary are both white, and have similar magnitudes, though the primary is slightly brighter.
Gray, slightly bluish, can see a tiny disc. Suspect a moon on the South side, a dot that pops into view occasionally.

Bright haze all around the moon, can't see the dark side.  At 9:38:43, the star just blinks out, instantly gone.  First detected reappearance at 10:33:14. Couldn't detect that Gamma Cap emerged for probably 20-25 seconds from the predicted time since the moon and clouds were so bright. The star was relatively small and dim. Still very cool to see, and the star "moved away" from the moon surprisingly fast.
Clavius has a smooth looking interior, with nice chains of craters inside.
Bullialdus has a peak in the middle, and walls look like double concentric rings. Bright white thin ring around the top. A: looks fairly flat. B: looks bowl-shaped.
Primary is bright white. Secondary is much dimmer, also white. Primary is a little fuzzy; bad seeing or collimation is off.
Somewhat dim cluster, rather round. Slight concentration at the center. Nice double in the middle, circled.
Quite faint. Slightly brighter in the center. Circular? Can't determine shape for sure.
Mini double cluster! Both very open, no areas of concentration. 1807 is larger, on the left.
Primary is golden, secondary is blue. Fairly strong color contrast. Nice pair.
Nice bright, wide cluster. Aldeberan is yellow-orange. Nice tight hexagon of stars at the bottom.
Both stars are white. Given the seeing, these go from clearly separated to a single oval blob.
Main feature is a nice right triangle, with a trail of three stars on one edge.

Can see the secondary as a tiny stationary dot of the diffraction rings of the primary. No particular color; white. Can see two 75% complete rings most of the time, with spikes of rings moving around.
Primary, secondary both white. Close, but cleanly split. Primary maybe 1 mag brighter?
Just for fun. Star are bright pinpoints. Very beautiful.

Nebula is surprisingly bright and detailed given the moon. Trapezium stars have tiny diffraction rings; can't see any other components (E/F). A treat, but a pain to sketch. Theta2 - both white, similarly bright, though star on the left is the primary.
A,B are Struve 747. A is slightly brighter. Both white. C is iota-Ori, can see much dimmer secondary. All white.  Nice open cluster!
Deep crater with a flat bottom. Lighter (rougher) area at the S part.
Nice area! Heroditus is a very cool teardrop shape, with what looks like a river flowing out.
Very star, strong shadows. bottom seemed fairly smooth, but walls are very rough.
Very similar magnitudes. A is slightly orange, B is slightly bluish.
Faint bright patch around two stars.
Large, extremely faint circular blur. Slightly brighter -- a hit of a dot -- near the center. A = Azha = Eta Eri.  Had to know exactly where to look for this; wouldn't have seen it otherwise.
All stars somewhat blurry. No obvious color (gray-white). Lots of diffraction mes on the primary.
Close secondary appears as a dot in second diffraction ring of the primary. Maybe has a hint of red. Far star is much dimmer.
Very faint fuzzy patch. Center is slightly brighter.  Near Al Kab.
Brighter fuzzy spot with bright core. Looks like a globular cluster. Modestly bright - could detect without having to stare at where it should be first.
Fain, somewhat small globular. Center is brighter. Can't resolve any stars; fuzzy.
Beautiful, wide double. Primary is yellow, secondary is deep orange.
Very dim, but extremely deep red. (Reddest star I've ever seen.) Very cool.
Nice clear, bright open cluster. No strong concentration in the center. Maybe 30 stars. Very sparkly.
Primary is bright, secondary just a faint dot. Clean split. Both stars white. The "noise" on primary is very stable, small.
Secondary (marked) is extremely dim but has a large separation. This whole area looks like a very sparse open cluster. Not all stars drawn.  (This shows the double with sep 58" PA 10.)
Very close double. Secondary is between second and third diffraction ring. Bi is secondary with sep 2.3", PA 67", C another very faint star.
Very Sparse. Not many stars. Invisible in finder scope. Very near M 47, which is much brighter.
Very rich section of the sky. Lots of nearby clusters. This one is relatively bright and compact. Would call this the "Fish Cluster".
Modestly close, but clean separation. Both stars are white, but primary is perhaps a little bluer and the secondary a little redder.
Primary seems slightly bluish, secondary is slightly reddish, but both are pretty close to white.  Bright star near the center is struve 948, another double.
Stars are white, have similar magnitudes, though primary is brighter.
Very faint, looks like 2 m&m's. Westward cluster appears to have many fainter stars that I can't clearly resolve.
Fairly bright. Can see dimmer outer layer and brighter center. Under lower power, disappears with direct vision and appears bright with averted vision.
Fairly open cluster. Very crisp and clear. Top set of stars look like a ladder.

Lots of very faint stars. Middle almost looks slightly gray. Most stars are faint, hard to draw. Don't see a particular concentration at the center. Shape is roughly circular. (Finally! this was tricky to spot!)  Could not detect NGC 2438 in the cluster.
Very faint cluster. Appears roughly circular. Not too many stars. Area indicated seems gray since stars are hard to make out.
Wide separation, primary significantly brighter than secondary. Primary is shimmering lots of colors since close to the horizon.
Approx equally bright. Can see clear separation (barely) since stars are flaring from the seeing. A seems redder, B bluer.
Lots of stars, with a bit of concentration in the center. Can see a coathangerish asterism in side. A bit dim.
Lots of (apparent?) double and triple stars. Very bright.
Primary has slight orange tinge. Secondary very dim, just outside the noise of primary.
Stars are slightly orangey, but mostly white. Primary is a little brighter.
Wide split at this magnitude. Primary is yellow, secondary is lavender. Spectacular!
Stars are white. Primary is a bit brighter than secondary. Not a very clean split. Secondary is a stable dot in the primary's noisy diffraction pattern.
Faint roughly circular gray patch.  Seems almost transparent.
Fairly concentrated cluster. About 20-30 modestly bright stars, and many more at the edge of visibility. (Took 3 attempts to find this!)
Looks like a defocused star. Bright, hazy circle, center is brighter.  Without filter, appears similar, but a little smaller and brighter.
Primary very bright (can see spider vanes slightly). Secondary is dim. Both stars are white.
Extremely faint, long and thin. Right at the edge of detectability. Can only glimpse occasionally, with averted vision. This is almost at zenith; probably can't do better than this in Bellevue.
Secondary is a faint dot, just separated from brilliant primary. Unable to see with shorter focal length eyepieces. This one was hard.
M 81 has a fairly bright core, and is rounder. M 82 is long and thin, a little dimmer. Center is still brighter than the extremities.
Both stars equal brightness and both white.
Small, fairly bright. Core is brighter. Elliptical. No detail.
Larger and fainter than M 96. Roughly circular. Core is a bright dot.
Left one, M105, is a little brighter. Both look like fuzzy stars. Bright cores, elliptical. Right one, NGC 3384, is more elongated.
Small, medium brightness. Identified as a "faint fuzzy" before confirming location. Core is brighter, elongated a little.
Large faint gray blur. Center is not much brighter. Circular. Lots of stars in the field of view; not all show since it's so cold and windy.
Almost looks like a dim globular. Bright in center na appears slightly mottled. Circular. Fairly large with averted vision.
Primary is whitem secondary is orangeish, maybe half the size of the primary.
Bright core, slightly elongated, though with averted vision the outer area seems a little more circular.
Rather fain. Very near a star. Center is only slightly brighter; not too concentrated.
Fairly faint, but has a bright dot in the core. Slightly elongated.
Very similar, almost identical. Faint. Centers are a little brighter, but still soft. M 84 on the left is slightly brighter. These are part of Markarian's chain.
Dim. Slightly brighter at the core. Roughly circular.
Primary is bright white. Secondary is dim gray, maybe orangeish? Easy split.
Both stars are bright and shimmering--very near horizon. Split by about one star width. Stars very close in brightness.
Mairan looks round and bowl-shaped. Area around looks very rough. Mons Gruithuisen gamma and delta appear softer. Delta appears a little bigger and diamond-shaped; gamma is smaller and rounder.
Very pretty double! Easily split. Primary is golden, secondary a little dimmer and bright blue.
Very small faint smudge. Core seems brighter--almost seems like a faint fuzzy star.
Barely detectable hazy patch. Center is not noticeably brighter. Circular? Only see occasionally, momentarily. Hard to see any detail.
Extremely faint. Only occasionally seen with averted vision. Appears long and narrow. Core is not much brighter.
Very faint, on edge of detectability. Seems large, circular. Middle seems slightly brighter than the edge. Nicely framed in a triangle asterism within a larger triangle in the finder.
Appears as some nebulosity around a double star (A) and another fuzzy star (B).  [Verified afterwards that B is the center and M88 extends outwards through A, and down below.]
Very close, like two circles almost touching. Both equal brightness. Both slightly yellowish.
Primary maybe twice as bright as secondary. Close split, but clean. Separated by about the width of the secondary. Stars yellowish.
Primary about twice as bright as secondary. Tight but clean split. Would say slightly wider than Algieba. Both stars white.
Fairly dim, though visible direct vision. Roughly circular. Center is brighter. With averted vision almost seems sparkly.

A: M60 is relatively bright. Circular, brighter core. Elliptical? B: NGC 4638, very dim, need averted vision to see. This also has a brighter core. Seems longer and thinner. C: M59: put in the view since I realized I could!
Rather large, pretty dim, with direct vision. See core as a star, while core is brighter, it's still pretty diffuse. Couldn't make out and details/structure.
Core is brighter, visible with direct vision. Rest is moderately large with averted vision, somewhat dim.
Modestly bright. Direct vision. Roughly circular. Center is brighter.
Very faint, only see sometimes with averted vision. But, can see a distinct brighter core halfway between a single and a double star. Some nebulosity going all the way between them.
Very faint -- only see occasionally with averted vision. Just a slightly lighter patch in the view. Very diffuse, core is not much brighter than the edges.
Small and rather bright. Elongated. Core is brighter. Nice bright asterism pointing to it nearby.
Fairly dim, only visible with averted vision. Looks elongated. core is a brighter ellipse, just next to a dim star. Outar part seems rounder.

Primary bright and yellow. Secondary is dimmer, maybe by 2 magnitudes. Even with great seeing, this is a tough spilt. Secondary is only seen occasionally, and nearly touches the primary, usually obscured by the noise of the primary.
Primary is much brighter than secondary. Primary slightly yellow, secondary is white. Wide split.
Primary white, maybe twice as bright as secondary, which looks bluish. Wide separation, obvious even in finder scope.
Primary is light yellow, secondary is light blue. Fairly similar brightness. Very clean split.
Primary is considerably brighter than secondary. Primary is yellow, secondary looks orange. Fairly close, but clean split. :)
Both stars are white. Primary maybe twice as bright as secondary. Very clean split.
Large, fairly bright fuzzy ball. Slightly brighter in center. No stars resolved.
Galaxy appears to be face-on. Center is slightly brighter, and "pointed"--possibly hints of spiral arms.
Elliptical galaxy? Core is a very bright dot; starlike.

Core is concentrated and bright; star-like. Past that, center seems long and thin and brighter. Then with averted vision, see faint large halo. Generally rather faint. Half of view obscured through trees; had to wait to see the full picture.
Nice triangle of stars with another 2 (3?) centered in the middle. Points the way to M104.
Both stars are white. both fairly bright. Primary maybe 1-2 mags brighter. Close, but clean easy split.
Binocular double! Primary bright and slightly yellow tint. Secondary far apart, dimmer, white. Also a good name.
Primary is gold, secondary is blue. Very pretty. Easily split, even at 30x.

Another double double! :) Struve 1999 - both stars rather faint. One on the left is slightly brighter. Both stars white. Xi Sco: Primary much brighter, a little yellowish. Secondary is faint and white. Separation a little less than Struve 1999.
Big and bright. Can see two bands clearly, and one faintly. Poor seeing this low in the sky.
Very large, very faint, but individual stars are resolved.  Only a little denser toward the core.
Somewhat dim, given the magnification. Mottled appearance, can't clearly resolve any stars. Very hard to locate given it was so low to the horizon. Invisible even in 25mm eyepiece.
Deep, saturated orange. Fairly bright.
Primary is a little brighter, and is slightly yellow. Secondary is slightly blue. Very easy split.
Very similar brightness. Think A is brighter. Both stars are white.
Very bright and sparkly. Many stars resolved without averted vision. Always a favorite!
Very nice pair of equally bright, white stars. Can split easily in finder scope.
Tight double, but clean split. Both stars look equally bright and white.
Nice triple! All stars are white. Brightest stars seem about equal brightness; third is a bit dimmer and just separated (cleanly).
Both stars white. Primary is somewhat brighter than secondary (1 mag?)
Primary is very bright and sparkly. Secondary is very dim, just a speck. More stars visible in the view but not drawn.
Bright core and fuzzy edges. Note even other stars are fuzzy at this magnification, but this is bigger.  No other details resolved.
Both stars are yellow. Secondary (B) may be slightly more orangey. Primary a little brighter than secondary. Primary (A) supposedly also a double, but can't split even with 4.5mm.
Primary is a bright orange; can see diffraction rings (and spikes). Secondary is white, and just a dot. Clean split.
Stars are nearly equal magnitude. A is slightly brighter, I think. A is white (hint of blue). B is slightly yellow.
Moderately faint cotton ball. Core is brighter. No stars resolvable.
Two bands visible. See the great red spot!  GRS is pinkish, darkest on top.  White area next to it. At the equator, slightly darker between the bands.
Primary looks like it may be yellower and secondary whiter, but both stars are colorful and spiky (too much atmosphere).
Stars are about equal brightness. Stars yellow? Color is hard to determine.
Primary is bright white, secondary is maybe one magnitude dimmer and light orange.
Brighter stars in the cluster form a triangular grid. Very open cluster, not much central concentration.
Sharp long shadows. Rupes Recta very prominent and straight. Right at lunar sunrise.
Hesiodus A looks relatively steep. Sharp shadows. Bowl shaped.
Looks very smooth and round. Center has a bum. Hints of ridge around the inside of the rim.
Kies is just the outer rim of a crater--the bottom is flat. Pi is a nearby smooth bump. Remember looking for this last year; have to have the light just right to see Kies Pi.
Hainzel is mostly obscured by two smaller craters on top of it. At the center of A, C there's a small pointy hill.
Hills look low and generally smooth. Arranged in a wavy N-S direction.
Several brighter stars, then with averted vision, appears to be a large number of faint ones in a small area. No concentration at center.
Very bright! Open cluster a bit concentrated at the center. Would be cool to see from a lower latitude.  Not visible through finder.
Main stars make a chevron shape, of which the farthest east (marked) is reddish.
Very faint. With averted vision, can see a faint fuzzy patch. Brighter in the center. Speckled appearance.
Very faint (though brighter than M 69). Can see a fuzzy patch, speckled. Brighter at the center.
Fairly bright fuzzy patch. Very concentrated in center. Slightly speckled. No stars resolved.
Extremely faint cluster. Stars are separated, but can only see them occasionally with averted vision. Cluster is pretty large.
Found slightly by accident. Always a favorite, though. Forgot how straight the hanger is.
Rather loose cluster of stars. Maybe 30 stars. Slightly concentrated towards the center.
It seems like there's some nebulosity along the chain of stars past the main center star on the left, and another lighter patch in a curve on the right.
Misty halo around Jupiter. No detail on the planet. Io is barely visible, about one Jupiter-width away.
All moons neatly lined up. No detail on Jupiter, just a bright disc.
Indeed, a backwards 5. End stars are brighter, the rest are pretty faint.
Stars are pretty bright. Recognizable as a somewhat distorted teapot!
Orangy, a little reddish. Fairly bright.
Whole thing is slightly elliptical, but there's an apple-core-shaped brighter area. Nicely centered in a square of stars.
Bright, very small and star-like. See a little fuzz with averted vision.
Tiny and cute. Aww! Yellow. Can't quite make out which part of Saturn is in front of the rings.
Jupiter just a white dot. Moon closest to Jupiter [Io] very hard to see.
Jupiter sometimes has a halo as thin clouds pass through.
Moon has a cloud over it, seeing and transparency pretty bad. Large, rocky mountain in center of crater.
Io is very close to Jupiter--hard to see and much dimmer than the other moons.
Fuzzy, rather like a slightly out of focus star. Fairly bright.
Beautiful open cluster. Very rich, seems to be part of a larger star field that won't fit in the field of view.

Ritter and Sabine both flat; Sabine has a dark shadow on the right; Ritter has a bright light on the left.  This is where the Apollo 11 mission took place on 1969-07-20 (almost 50 years ago to the day!) where Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin were the first people to set foot on the moon.
Jupiter - bright and white, as always. Distances on diagram are in Jupiter-widths.
Polaris is quite bright - a nice diamond in the ring. Great (and useful) asterism. "x" marks the approximate north celestial pole.
While bright, Megrez is a little hard to see tonight; have to stare at it for a few seconds before I can see it.
Upper quadrangle is the keystone.
Cygnus completely visible tonight -- often the tips of the wings are hard to see. Many more stars not drawn here.
Io is again faint and near Jupiter. Hard to see.
Pale orange color, with a hint of red.
Orangy-red. Fairly saturated color. Really stands out.
Bright and glittery. See lots of stars, not all resolved. Center is bright. Est class IX.
These appear much smaller than drawn in the circle. Can't see Callisto, even at higher powers.
Jupiter a smeary white dot. Can't see Europa.
Dist from Jupiter to nearest moon is about 1/3 Jupiter.
Fairly bright fuzzy ball. If I stare directly at it, it disappears! Fun! Nice double star a bit directly W makes this easy to find.
First moon west of Jupiter is brightest.
Actually a believable asterism - nice hexagon with two streamers. Right a zenith, what a pain!
V-shape of Hyades. Stars are very bright and easy to find next to Beta-Oph
Can only see 3 moons. With 8mm eyepiece, can still only see 3 moons, but can see the bands of Jupiter!
Somewhat faint cluster, but glittery. Lots of stars, maybe about 10 somewhat brighter ones.
Not too saturated; at first glance has hardly any color. Light red, slightly orangey. Not too bright.
Bright and brilliant red-orange. More on the orange side. Best carbon star I've seen in awhile.
Basically white. Slight yellowish tinge.
Fairly dim. Can't resolve any detail, just a gray circular ball.  Top part seems a little brighter.
Bright stars in the field. Faint crescent of nebulosity around the central 4 stars. Brightest on the west side. Very cool.
Io is very close to Jupiter, very faint and hard to see.
Fairly deep orange, hint of red,
The dot in a question mark asterism! Very light orange, not much saturation. Almost a little yellow.

NGC 6791 on the right. Very faint open cluster with many dim stars. U Lyr on the left. Deep red, pretty dim also. Weird effect that the triangle originally takes averted vision to see, and U is colorless, but then if I focus on U then other stars disappear and the color on U becomes obvious.
Mostly a gray blur, but can can see some sparkly stars with averted vision, and the core seems brighter. Est class IX.
Almost star-like. Very small, bright core. Faint halo around it. Est class I.
Moon near jupiter is very faint.
Does look like orion, though the belt seems angled the wrong way.
Doesn't look like a horseshoe to me, though I matched the field of view to the expected location.  (Seems like I can zoom in a bit many places and see horseshoe patterns of stars?)
Pale orange color.
Very pale orange; mostly white. Distinctive run of stars to the S.
Moon on the right is dimmest.
Fun to see white it's still light out! Jupiter was visible naked-eye at 8:50, but couldn't see moons in the telescope at that time.
A bit turbulent, even at this low power.
Ganymede is brightest, followed by Europa. Callisto is dimmest. Can see them appear separately as it gets dark.
Can see the "5 Pointed Star" asterism. 7 stars.
Very bright, easy to find. Nice smiley face! Too big for 10" scope.
Bright orange star. Fairly vibrant.
Right near zenith, so view rotates every time I recenter! AF: white, slightly yellow. AW: much dimmer, deep orange.
A curved 7 shape made up of 11-12 stars.
Two curvy shapes (fish hooks) connected to a bright yellow star (marked).
Barely visible with averted vision naked eye, but very bright in binoculars.
Io is faint; can only see sometimes when not in Jupiter's blur.
Looks like a thin tennis racket. Easy to find and identify.
Bright asterism, easily recognizable.
Has a slight ring appearance. The N side, away from the adjacent star, seems slightly brighter, making it look a little crescent shaped.
Rather faint, but very rich cluster. Hundreds of stars. Can resolve maybe 10 stars with averted vision; the rest just appear as a sparkly gray patch.
Deep brick red. Part of a little Cassiopeia asterism.
Fairly bright. A pinkish-orange color. Rich area of the sky. Many more stars visible; only the brighter ones drawn.
Guessing that the asterism is the little chain of stars with the Y on the end. Doesn't look like much, but matches the center of the FOV in the picture.
Very faint, only visible with averted vision. Slightly concentrated near the center, can see maybe 50 stars.
Beautiful ring of double stars. very cool and recognizable. :)
Looks like three blades of a fan; don't see the emu. Pretty bright though. Marked star has a tinge of orange red.
Looks like a double. One on the left is light, but deep orange. Other is blue.
Rather faint. Sort of a trapezoid. Can only see 3 stars without averted vision.
Quite bright, fairly saturated orange. Really stands out. :) Lots of glittery stars in the view.
Very bright, light orange. Not very saturated.
Somewhat dim. See maybe 20 modestly dim stars encircled by 5 brighter ones. Then averted vision hints at many more even dimmer stars.
Fuzzy ball, brighter in the center. With averted vision see a star in the center.
Loos cluster, no strong concentration. Maybe 20-30 stars.

ObjIds: Old moon in new moon's arms
Notes: Dark side of moon is lighter than the surrounding sky. Not enough contrast to make out much detail, but can get hints of the major oceans and mare.
Can't quite resolve any stars. But with averted vision has a slightly speckled appearance. Est class V.
Bright, not reddish at all, just a pale yellow.
A bit dim, but looks like a flyswatter.
Arrowhead shaped. Between two bright stars (one outside FOV).
Rather faint. Hints of some stars on the outside, but mostly just a gray patch. Est class IX.
Took a long time to find. Seems like a very sparse open cluster. Can sort of see a mushroom.
Can't see too much detail, but it's clear to see one side is in shadow. Appears to be a darker band across the center. Can see the Cassini band some moments.
Very little central concentration. Stars are dim and rather spread out. Est class X
Looks a bit like an airplane viewed from above.
Don't see much of a yacht. There's a nice zigzag of 4 star and an arc - looks like the letters SC in this orientation.
Fairly bright and recognizable as a pipe.
Primary is yellow, secondary is just a point, but looks orange.
Y shape. Bright enough to be seen as a blur naked eye.
Nice bright circle of 6 stars with a little tail. Lots of fainter stars (not drawn) sparkling in the background.
Long S-shaped pattern with many faint stars.
Faint nebulosity around the center of stars in the middle. Eastward, possible very faint nebulosity throughout.
Fairly bright, modestly light orange red. Looks white at first glance.
Very pale orange. Makes the other (white) stars look blueish.
Fairly bright, somewhat saturated orange.
Very dim. Medium orange. Looks white-gray most of the time, but with averted vision see more color.
Very bright, vibrant orange-red. Next to a line of 4 stars.
Very pale, dim, mostly white, with a hint of orange-red.
Love this cluster. Bright eyes, very recognizable as an owl spreading its wings.
Bright, pale brick red.
Bright triangle of stars. Can see very faintly with naked eye.
Gray disc. Edges slightly fuzzy. Can't see Oberon or Titania. (Possibly glimpsed with averted vision, but can't distinguish vs other stars at the border of visibility.)
Pale pink, hint of orange. Fairly bright.
Very pale, light orange.
Very pale orange. Not too bright.
UY And: medium deep red orange. Rather faint. NGC 1023: Elongated elliptical. Bright core - looks like a faint star at lower powers. Two in the view!
Bright, vibrant orange.
Very very pale peach color.
Very bright, vibrant light orange.
Basically white; slight tinge of yellow.
Four brighter stars make the spatula part, and 5 dimmer stars make a handle.
No stars visible naked eye, though I've seen it before at darker sites. Just SE of the great square of Pegasus.
Basically white, just a hint of yellow.
Nice open cluster shape of D is apparent, formed with 5 brighter stars and 5 fainter stars.
Can see an S shape after some staring, as indicated.
Bright, obvious question mark! (Backwards in refractor). Like it!
Doesn't look like much, but matched the field of view. Fainter stars require averted vision to see.
Very bright, super vibrant brick orange. Really stands out! :)
Looks like a kite with a long tail. Marked star is bright and has a yellow tint.
Appears mostly white; very slightly yellow.
Fairly vibrant, modestly deep red-orange.
Distinct black dot near the edge of the disc. Only saw for about 30 seconds; rest of the time too cloudy to see anything.
Bright gray disc. Soft edges, can see some turbulence. No hint of any moons.
Fairly bright, looks like a star. Hint of yellow/red tone.
Very bright and glittery! Beautiful. Do see spirals of stars towards the center. :)
Small, not too faint. A bit elongated, center is brighter.
Roughly circular. Looks like a star with nebulosity.
Very faint, can only see stars with averted vision. Rather diffuse, center not too concentrated. Est class X.
Faint nebulosity around the two central stars.
Found by accident! Beautiful open cluster. Lots of stars, fairly dense. Bit like a christmas tree or a half-opened umbrella.
Can see E and F stars! Bright nebulosity!
Appears stellar, as a "fat" star. Some astigmatism? At 9mm appears gibbous.
Very bright.
Bright, recognizable circle of stars in the Hyades. Star marked Y has a yellow tint.
Looks like Scorpius! Bright, need low power.
Curved S of roughly equal magnitude stars. Framed by Mintaka (Delta Ori) and Anilam (Epsilon Ori).
Six stars making an elongated triangle. Right next to Gamma Ori. Because of increasing haze, no other stars visible in the view.
Nice set of 7 stars around Delta CMa
Don't see much of a gun here, but there is a nice triangle of star near Gamma Mon.
Slightly jagged line of faint stars. Bright star in SW is Zeta Tau.
Arc of about 10 stars around a central star.
Faint fuzzy disc. Only visible with averted vision.
Deep, vibrant orange-ochre color.
Comet-like. Shaped like an arrowhead. The head is very bright, almost stellar, and the tail fades off. Generally pretty bright.
Vibrant red-orange, maybe 2/3 orange and 1/3 red.
Pale orange color, very bright.
Don't see a little Leo constellation. Looks like a backwards 1.
Really great 3 shape. Very obvious. :)
Light orange color. Bright.
Fairly pale, peach color. Bright triplet of stars nearby helps to locate this.
6 stars in a slanted ladder. (Don't see a shrimp.)
Bright star is 19 Pup. Faint, spread out open cluster. No central concentration. Many more stars seen with averted vision. Might be worth checking this out at a darker site.
Vaguely umbrella shaped; like a cross between an umbrella and a coat hanger. Big and bright. Brightest star in the middle is yellow.
Bright fuzzy ball when using the filter, seems to have a faint ring around it. Very cool.
Appears as faint nebulosity between them. Center is a little brighter, core appears starlike (or there is a star there).
Looks circular. Core is brighter. Seems a little mottled.
NGC 4088 is large, elliptical, and very dim. Core not much brighter/concentrated. NGC 4085 is small, elliptical also. Core is more concentrated. Both galaxies barely detectable.
Small, bright, elliptical. Core is starlike.
Small, elliptical. Fairly dim. Core is a bit brighter. Very close to barely naked-eye star Chi UMa.
Head of Leo. Unmistakable. Mu is visible only with averted vision.
Small, super bright, roughly semicircle phase, though hard to see through astigmatism spikes. At 8mm (50x) can see more detail.
Looks like a slightly defocused double star with some extra nebulosity. Hard a hard time finding this without the filter.
Fairly large. 2x1 aspect ratio. Not much concentration at the center. Whole thing is a bit faint. Small star-like dot at the core.
Very long and thin. Bright. Appears to have a bulge in the middle.
Diffuse and dim. Core not bright. Elliptical? 5x1 aspect ratio.
Line of 6-7 stars. Looks like a two-pronged fork.
Looks like a lambda, but can vaguely see this as an upside-down sailboat.
Asterism is clear--can see a horseshoe shape with a bright star (diamond) with the two other stars broken off. Very near beta UMa.
Bright and sparkly! Looks like a ladder. :)
Faint, sparse open cluster. Hints of nebulosity (probably fainter stars I can't resolve) near the center.
Peach orange, fairly bright. Some stars in the FOV not drawn.
Bright orange, fairly saturated.
3 brighter stars in the shape of a chevron. 5-6 others seen with averted vision occasionally. H = HIP34357.
Pale orange-yellow. Not much saturation.
Same color as orange sodium lights.
Very very pale orange, nearly white. Hard to find.
Part of a funnel-like asterism. Deep orange (2/3) - red (1/3). Saturated.
Light orange, tinge of yellow. Fairly vibrant.
Clean, easy split. Primary a big blob, secondary a small dot.
Super bright vibrant orange, like a sodium light. :)
Deep orange, touch of red. Very saturated, colorful.
Fairly faint pale light orange. White a first glance, but can see color after closer inspection.
Very bright orange (2/3) - yellow (1/3). Medium saturation. Nice square asterism. :)
Very faint. Somewhat deep red (1/2) - orange (1/2).
Brightest 6 stars make a wide hear. Including the fainter stars, however, looks more like a double-bladed axe.
Very recognizable camel. Bright star is the head. Even has a faint star for the top of the hump.
Very bright, glittery. Marked star is U Hya, bright and golden carbon star.
6 dim stars in a V shape.
Run of 11 faint stars in a straight line. Pretty nice.
M65 is brighter, bigger and rounder than M66. Both are faint, both point N/S. Very cool that I can see these with only 80mm aperture!
Seems exactly half-phase.
Shape hard to determine, but seems football shaped.
Right at zenith, hard to determine W. Fairly bright. Bright core. 3:1 aspect ratio.
Large, skinny, very faint - just slightly lighter than the sky in a long thin patch. Diffuse; core not noticeably brighter.
Large, bright, circular. Core is brighter and elliptical. Barred? [No, elliptical.]

3 in the view! 3607 is biggest, bright, roughly circular. Very bright core. 3608 is a little bit dimmer, about the same size, but more elliptical, say 1.5:1. 3605 is much dimmer, smaller, but also has a bright core.
Generally circular. Starlike core. Central region is brighter in N/S direction. Possibly hints of arms at top and bottom? [Yes, is a spiral galaxy.]
Big, narrow, not too dim. Core is slightly brighter than the edges.
Bright, core seems to have a C shape, though hard to nail down.
Very small, very bright. Core is almost stellar.
Long and very thin. Very faint, hard to see.
Faint. Core is only a little brighter. 3:2 aspect ratio.
Very bright, at the end of a short chain of stars. Deep amber-orange color.
Sparse but very bright open cluster in Orion, bottom of sword. iota-Ori is a double star (marked). Looks like a leaf hanging from a branch.
Faint, big and narrow. Center third is a little brighter.
Extremely faint. Can only glimpse momentarily with averted vision and moving the scope. Long and thin.
Round. Very small. Core is brighter. Right next to a double star. :)
Deep red-orange. Star is bright and saturated. Obvious color. No other stars except the two others drawn in the view.
Deep red orange, maybe 2/3 red and 1/3 orange. Very saturated.
Long and thin. Core is almost stellar. Surprisingly good for something this far in the southern murk.
Core is bright. Dot in the center. 2:1 aspect ratio.
Medium orange color. Fairly saturated. Lots of stars nearby.
Very pale orange. Rather faint. C is the end of a chan of 7 or 8 dim stars that point to the star.
Light apricot orange. Not too saturated. Surrounded by a half ring of 5 bright stars.
Pale orange with a hint of red. At first glance, hard to see any color.
Core looks stellar. Small, not too dim. Roundish, maybe 3:2 aspect ratio.
Small, rather faint. core not much brighter. Roundish.
Elliptical. Core is bright. Almost looks like a faint glob with direct vision, but with averted vision can see a greater extent of the galaxy.
Small, fairly bright core. Elliptical. 3:2 aspect ratio.
Small. Bright core. 3:2 aspect ratio.
3619 is fairly dim, elliptical, larger. 3613: small, bright core. 3:2 aspect ratio.  Two in the view!
Deep brick red color.
Faint. Usually appears white, but sometimes get a glimpse of orange.
Deep brick red.
At lower power (40x) was a super deep dark red. At this magnification, appears 2/3 red, 1/3 orange. Still pretty saturated.
Medium light orange, peachish. In a bright pentagon asterism.
Saturated sodium-light color
Pale light orange, not too bright.
Medium pale orange. Only 5 stars visible in FOV.
Bright light orange with a hint of red. Medium saturation.
Pale apricot color. Part of a large C shape.
7 bright stars including 82 UMa. Don't see a gas pump handle, looks more like a horse without a head.
Brightest stars make a sigma. Can see a potential Eiffel tower pointing to the south.
Bright peak in the middle. Floor is flat. Crater walls look very rough and mountainous.
Smooth and bowl-shaped. Rim looks raised. Brighter than the surrounding Mare Crisium.
Nice shovel, somewhat like the big dipper with a differently shaped handle. M53 in the view. :)
Looks a little like an arrow pointing west, or a partially closed umbrella.
Long line of faint stars near psi-Hya, the brightest star.
Round. Bright stellar core.
Very faint gray patch. Only visible occasionally. Don't see any concentration in the core.
Roughly circular. Stellar-looking core.
Quite faint. 2:1 aspect ratio. Core not very bright.
Very faint, just a gray smudge. No concentration at the core visible. 4:3 aspect ratio. Hard to detect; can only see intermittently.
4762 is long and thin. Bright core appears very sharp. 4754 is round, bright. Stellar core. :)
Waning crescent phase. Terminator is slightly fuzzy. The dark side is distinct against the sky.
Waning crescent phase. Dark side is brighter than the sky.
Faint. Roughly circular. Core is brighter, occasionally seems like a faint star. Mottled texture? Core seems 2:1 aspect ratio.
Medium bright. Stellar core, but when shaking the scope, see large extent of galaxy, maybe 2:1 aspect ratio.
Small, dim; star-like core.
4278: fairly bright starlike core. 4274: very faint. Appears as nebulosity around stars.
Bright starlike core. Rest is elusive; see glimpses of the rest of the galaxy but very faint, hard to determine shape and orientation.
Bright. Long and thin. :)
Round, bright stellar core.
Very faint, core slightly brighter; just a gray patch. Small.
4216 has a bright core. Long and thin. Modestly bright. 4206 (marked) appears starlike. Faintest bit of nebulosity occasionally seen.
4435: modestly bright core. 4438: a little small, fainter, and core not as bright.
4461: small. Bright core (but overall not that bright). 4456: very small, faint. Elusive.
Bright. Slightly speckled with averted vision. Est class VIII.
Large. Very faint and transparent. 4:1 aspect ratio. Core not bright.
Round, bright. Core almost stellar. Almost looks like a globular. Easy to find, midway between two brighter stars.
4564: very small; bright core. 4568: larger of the two twins. Roughly circular. 4567: smaller, more eccentric. Both 4567/8 are faint and elusive, and seem to overlap.
M87 (NGC 4486): big, bright, elliptical. 4:3 aspect ratio. 4486A: small, starlike. 4478: bright core but a little larger and more diffuse.
Faint. Core is a little brighter. Can see some brighter areas farther away - spiral arms?
Stellar core. Round.
Small. Bright stellar core.
Fairly bright. Stellar core. Small. 2:1 aspect ratio.
Fairly bright. Cire is a bit brighter. Round.
Faint, diffuse. Roughly circular. With averted vision can see some brightness in the core.
Very faint! Almost nebulous. One star is bright, another is dim, and the last two very dim. Difficult.
Bright white walls, flat smooth interior. Crater marked * has very deep/strong shadows.
Looks like a shark or a dolphin. Bright tail with 4 stars. :)
Basically white; only a slight yellow tint.
Nice crescent shape, like a 4-5 day moon. Larger than in previous observations. Can barely make out the dark side against the sky.
Flat interior, but whole crater looks raised relative to the outside. Craterlets A,B,M look bowl-shaped.
Promontorium Laplace has a long triangular shadow that we can use to estimate the height of Prom. Laplace.
Pi appears as a small bump. Milichius and A are bowl shaped.
Very close to the moon tonight! Very bright, vibrant, deep red-orange. Really stands out! :)
Faint. Dim deep orange-red. Saturated. Bright stars nearby are mag 8.44 and 9.75.
Thin crescent, like a 4 day moon. At higher powers, crescent is more obviously thinner.
See a nice kangaroo back, a front leg, and two ears at the top. :) Just next to delta-Boo.
Doesn't look like much, but a nice modestly bright set of stars. Diamond-like.
Extremely faint, loose cluster. Can see 20-30 stars occasionally, but hard to pin down exact position of them Est Class XII.
Looks bigger and thinner than before, like a 3 day moon.
Bright diamond stars in the shape of a fish hook. :) Marked star is E Hya.
Looks like a faint star. Mag 12.85. 2400M light years away! Most distant object I can probably see with this telescope. :)
Vibrant, bright, color of a sodium light.
Very bright. Blue color. Solid ball with fuzzy edges. UHC filter doesn't show more detail. :)
Blurry, but looks gibbous. Close to Venus, making this possible to find.
Faint. Elliptical. 3:2 aspect ratio. Core not concentrated.
Faint. Long and thin. Core is brighter.
Very faint, thin cluster. May 20-30 stars appear intermittently with averted vision. Est class XI.
Super faint. A few stars flicker at the edge of detection. Core is a slightly brighter patch. Est class X.
Very bright. A cotton ball of stars in the middle. Many stars resolve. Brightest stars forma smiley face. Est class VI. :)
Very thin crescent, like a 2 day moon. Slightly larger, not visible naked eye.
Flat bottom, angled wall. Two hills inside; one at the center and another long thin one.
Large, flat-bottomed, with a central peak that looks like two white pointy teeth.
Baily - looks flat and shallow. Baily A - looks bowl shaped. Lacus Mortis - is dominated by Burg in the center, with a ridge on each side. Can see a general darker circular area of the Lacus.
Looks like an umbrella or a mushroom.
Small cluster of 5 stars, plus a few very faint ones.
Bright tangerine orange.
Fairly bright, speckled pattern. Some faint stars just resolving with averted vision. Est class VI.
Sort of a geometric question mark shape.
Deep 2/3 red, 1/3 orange. A little dim but very saturated.
Big and bright. Visible in finder scope. Hundreds of stars resolved (though not carefully plotted here). Est class VII.
Looks like a hat!
Bright and concentrated. Can see some stars resolved with averted vision. Est class III.
Very large, faint. Spread out. Lots of individual stars only seen with averted vision. Est class IX.
Bright, sparkly! Fuzzy cotton ball in the middle. :) Est class VIII.
Larger and dimmer than M 10. Bright, faintly concentrated core. Lots of stars resolved. Est class IV.
Seems like this would be pretty bright if this were above the murk. Speckled appearance, hints of lots of stars with averted vision. Est class V.
Small, dim. No stars resolved. Fairly concentrated core. Est class IV.
Very faint and diffuse. Slight speckling. Only visible with averted vision. Est class XI.
Crucifix cluster! Very cool. Faint, slightly speckled. :) Est class V.
Very faint. Not too concentrated. Est class IX.
Fairly bright. Can see hundreds of stars, barely, with averted vision. Est class VIII.
Moderately bright fuzz ball. No stars resolved. Est class V.
Very pale orange. Not too bright.
Nearly white, just a pale yellow color.
Need averted vision to see all the stars.
Four bright stars, easy to spot.
Aristillus: has a soft bump in the middle. Autolycus: bowl shaped. Archimedes: large, flat basin. Bright/dark contrasty walls. Vallis Alpes: unexpected white and black line. Very prominent.
Rough oval of stars with one bright one on the side. Bright one is pale yellow (HD164922).
White, maybe the slightest hint of yellow. Wouldn't have guessed this is a carbon star; just matched the field of view.
Possibly an open cluster. Can see a cane-shaped pattern with 7 brighter stars and some fainter ones. Busy star field. Star marked H is HD 187344.
All are small pinpricks. A: white, B: much fainter. C: faint orange tint. :)
Primary very bright. C and D are dim. C looks like a double star too.
A is slightly brighter than B. C is dimmer, and D is very faint. All stars white.
Tight double double. Only barely split A,B. Need perfect collimation for this.
Primary is bright gold. Secondary much smaller and white.
Very faint; can't see all the time. Not too concentrated. Mostly just a blur but occasionally see hints of stars. Est class IX.
Large. Fairly dim. No stars resolved, but has slightly speckled appearance. Est class VII.
Bright star HR6453 just out of view to the W. Very dim, sparse, and diffuse. Est class XII.
Spectacular! Can see dust lanes, e.g., the propeller, and "star arms" coming off of it. Est class V.
Gray disc with averted vision. With direct vision, center seems smaller and brighter. Need a gas filter to see more detail.
Very large and sparse. See individual dim stars. One area (marked) seems fuzzy. Perhaps this is the core? If so, est class I.
Bright, concentrated at the center, speckled appearance, but can't see individual stars. Est class V.
Modestly faint and diffuse, though visible at 40x magnification. Hints of stars at periphery. Est class IX.
Westmost point of a double triangle asterism. Sodium-light orange. Modestly saturated. :)
Looks annular with averted vision. Also see a bright speck in the middle sometimes. Central star? [Likely not the central star, but there is a star there.]
Super big, bright. See 15-20 brighter stars distinctly; rest are speckled or faint to make out. Some dust band on W side. Est class VII.
Small, a little dim. No stars resolved. Est class VI.
Light apricot orange. At low power, really stands out as colored.
Rather pale sodium light color. Bright.
Just barely visible naked eye. Bright point of light with a round halo and a long tail. Slight second tail on N side.
Faint blurry spot. No stars resolved. Est class IX.
Very small and faint. Center almost looks stellar. Est class II.
Very faint, loose. Resolve individual stars intermittently. Slightly brighter at the core. Est class IX.
Very faint, elusive. Core is slightly brighter. Hints of stars with averted vision and jiggling the scope. Est class V.
Very bright. Slightly aqua colored disc without filter. With OIII filter, see a ring structure and a faint outer halo. :)
Possibly spiral. Center not too concentrated, but there is a central bulge, and hints of arms farther out.
Small and faint. Oval shaped. Core is only slightly brighter. Best seen with peripheral vision.
Moons from brightest to dimmest: I (Iapetus), T (Titan), R (Rhea), Te (Tethys), D (Dione). Can see rings are not as wide this year. Appears to be a band across the middle of Saturn.
Moons: G (Ganymede), E (Europa), I (Io), C (Callisto). Not too much detail visible with this seeing.
Fairly bright. Center not too concentrated. Speckled, but no stars resolved. Est class IV.
Center concentrated. No stars resolved, but speckled. Est class I.
Very diffuse and faint. Easy to lose in the view and barely seen against the background murk. Est class XI.
Somewhat faint. Large. Speckling of stars, but too dim to see any particular stars clearly. Est class V.
Small and bright. No stars resolved, but slight speckled appearance. Est class III.
Generally dim, but occasionally the center jumps into view. See individual stars, no fuzziness. Est class X.
Fuzzy cotton ball. Hints of some stars. Medium dim, but not elusive. Est class VIII.
Somewhat bright. Very open. About 10 brighter stars.
Right next to NGC 6755, but much smaller and fainter. Concentrated at center, almost looks like a globular.
Not visible naked eye. Very thin crescent, going about 1/3 of the way around the moon. Slight roughness at the terminator. [5 mins later, visible naked eye.]
Rima Ariadaeus: a thin crack, dark with very thin white edges. Boscovich P: long, thin elliptical crater. Manilius: Very round; sharp shadows.
Moderately bright; small; speckled. Very near bright mag 5 star nu2 Sgr. :) Est class III.
Small but bright. Obvious even at low power. No stars resolved, but slightly sparkly with averted vision. Est class IV.
Very pale orange. Clearly a carbon star, but not vibrant.
Bright vibrant vermillion. Interesting star pattern nearby. :)
Part of an upside down G asterism. Nearly white; faint yellow tint.
Very saturated bright orange. Similar to a sodium light, but a little deeper and redder. :)
Primary, secondary about equal magnitude. White, cleanly split. Third star very faint.
Primary A and secondary B ar both super bright mag 5, about equal. C is faint and nearby. Very easy to split.
Primary is super bright, secondary a distinct dot at the edge of the diffraction noise of A. C is quite faint.
A is gold, B is a faint small dot barely separated from A. C is blue, D is faint, white. Very nice! :)
Nice easy to split triple. Good for a smaller scope. C looks slightly brighter than B.
Pretty. Primary is slightly yellow; secondary deep orange, almost brown.
Circular. With averted vision seems like a brighter center and a fainter edge.
Primary is yellow. Secondary is a white dot. See nice diffraction pattern around the primary.
Bright; center very bright. Lots more field stars not drawn.
Looks like a med. bright star with direct vision. With averted vision, can see a fuzz ball.
M 10: brighter and has a more concentrated core. M 12: dimmer, less concentrated.
Bright, like a partially resolved globular. Not fuzzy. Have special memories of this since it was the first Messier object I "discovered" before knowing about it.
Small bright blurry patch. Only brightest stars drawn; see maybe 100 in the field.
Ultra-rich field of view, maybe 200 stars. M 29 appears as a bright hazy cluster, but can resolve some stars.
Vibrant deep orange, hint of red. bright.
Small pinpoint star. Sodium-light color Medium saturation.
Very pale brick red color, mostly white.
Mostly white; faint yellow tint.
Bright open cluster. Can see distinctly about 8 stars, and general fuzziness of more fainter ones. Centered in a nice arc of stars.

M 16: Fuzzy patch; with averted vision looks like a star in the center, two below, and one a above. M 17: Smaller, fainter fuzzy patch. Brighter at the center. M 18: Fuzzy patch. Brighter, larger and more diffuse than M 17. M 24: Brightest stars make a football shape. With averted vision lower area looks like it has a lot of nebulosity.
Very small and very bright. Phase is half.

ObjIds: New Moon in Old Moon's Arms
Notes: Can see more on the dark side quite clearly; harder to see near the terminator due to the brightness.
Open cluster, stars roughly equally bright. Looks a little like a spider.
Faint and fuzzy, no stars resolved. Est class VII.
Looks like a hat, or imaginatively, a snake eating an elephant, as in The Little Prince.
Has a bright line of 5 stars in a row. Est class I 3 m.
Bright, open cluster. Has one really bright star. Est class II 3 m.
Right next to 6885; Bright star in the center is "A" in 6885. Est class IV 3 p.
Fairly bright. Big. Looks like a tendril of smoke. :)
Faint and not very concentrated. Maybe 20 brighter stars and then a faint mist of many unresolved stars. Est class II 2 r.
Small, bright concentrated. Diverse stars. Many fainter stars not drawn. Est class I 3 m.
Rich, bright, small cluster. Brighter stars form a cross shape. Est class III 3 m.
Very faint. Just a med-size blur. Est class VIII.
Brightest globular in the Andromeda galaxy! Appears as a slightly fuzzy star, with two nearby stars making "Mickey Mouse" ears. Very hard to find. Est class V.
Bright, large open cluster. About 10 stars resolved, lots more appear as a sparkly haze with averted vision. Est class I 3 r. Mostly fainter stars in FOV not shown.
Has two "tails" with 6-7 brighter stars. Bright and slightly speckled. Bright core. Est class III.
Super big and bright! Speckled, but generally not resolved except for a few stars at the edge. Hints of brighter/darker patches - dust lanes? Est class VII.
Bright and sparkly, very concentrated core. In a pretty star field. Est class I.
Small, not too dense. Appears fuzzy at lower power (40x). Prominent stars form a rough line through the cluster. Est class II 2 p.
Faint. Nice ring structure. Reminds me of a dim M 57.
Small cluster. Faintest stars unresolved, look somewhat nebulous. Maybe 30 resolved stars. Est class II 3 m.
Primary is one of the bright stars in the coathanger cluster, Cr 399! And has a gold tint. B, C, D all are faint and white.
Primary (A) is brilliant, almost blinding for the other stars. B is very close, but just barely separated. C is super faint.
Another double-double! All stars are white. A-B very close. C-D farther separated, but D is rather faint.
A, C look equally bright. B is very close to A, and dim. Not well separated. D is easy to see.
Under higher power, A and C are bright and blurry. No sign of B here. However, with averted vision, can occasionally see E star, super dim at mag 13.
Sort of looks like a person. Bright star in SE is Enif, epsilon-Peg.
Flat base, distinct feature is the 'B' crater offset from the middle with a white ring.
Very bright. Slightly brownish orange color. Very saturated.
Bright stars, easily split. All are white. Good for a small scope. Primary is bright, second and third are about equal brightness.
Fairly bright, maybe 40 stars. Est class II 2 p. Shape of a Christmas tree.
Star appears white. No color, even when defocusing and trying higher powers.
Starlike, even at 63x. Pale blue.
Bright, easy. Looks like a sword, or maybe a rocket going SE.
Bright, saturated. About 1/3 red, 2/3 orange.
Pale orange, hint of yellow. Not too saturated, but stands out from other stars. Super close to Kemble's cascade.
Bright vibrant orange, hint of red.
Basically white, maybe the faintest tinge of yellow. Not apparent that this is a carbon star.
First time seen with any detail. Looks like a photo! Can see polar ice cap, dark patches. Pale orange.
Very pale, almost white. Faint yellow orange.
Cluster is very small. 5 brighter stars in a pentagon. Other stars not resolved, just a blurry patch. Another cluster NGC 7788 just at the border to the NW.
Well separated from background field. No strong concentration stars. Stars generally uniformly bright. About 20 stars. Est class III 1 p. Brightest stars from a rough crescent.
Very bright. Pale orange. Both polar regions whiter. Prominent dark like, and a fainter spot, both grayish.
Very poor, dim cluster. Only 4 obvious brighter stars, and maybe about 10 dim ones, at the edge of detectability. Est class III 3 p.
Found in the middle of a star hop, had to stop and look! Brightest star (right eye) is slightly yellowish. Looks like an owl. About 40 stars. Est class II 3 p.
Est class II 3 p. Small, sparse cluster. see 20-30 stars.

3 clusters in the view! K 14: roughly the shape of an alpha. Est class III 2 p. NGC 133: Has 5 brighter stars in the shape of a Y, and a few other very dim stars. Est class III 3 p. NGC 146: faint and poor. Est class II 2 p.
Sort of a triangular pinwheel shape. Small and bright. Marked is slightly orange. Slight nebulosity, as of many unresolved fainter stars in the cluster. Est class II 3 r.
Main feature is 4 bright stars in a tight row. Small, somewhat bright. Est class III 2 p.

All stars white. AB brightest, very difficult to split. B can only be seen occasionally and is very dim. C then D are next brightest. These are nearly touching, but cleanly split. E dimmer and F, G dimmer still, but visible with averted vision.
C is brightest, then A then B. All stars are bright and have similar magnitude (esp. A, B).
A bright, B, C dimmer. B is very close to A; difficult to split. C obvious, with averted vision, else difficult to see.
All stars white. A bright, C next brightest, D is dim, but visible with direct vision. B clearly separated from A but very dim; only see with averted vision.
Would order in brightness as A, B, E, C, D.  A, B, C are close together but are cleanly split.
Faint, round, flat disc. Edges slightly fuzzy. No detail.
Bright, large cluster. Maybe 60 stars. Est class II 3 m.
Fairly thin and long. Bright core.
Very faint. Round. Center slightly brighter. Face on galaxy.
Inside a larger, brighter cluster, Cr 33. Hard to distinguish. Suspect this cluster is the slight concentration of fainter stars. Est class IV 1 p.
Med size. Bright, pretty cluster. Looks like a mini Delphinus. :) Est class II 3 m.
Very faint stars; spread out. Est class II 1 m.
Small, bright. Eight stars near the center look like an anchor. At lowest power (finderscope) can see Rinnan's Run. :) Est class II 3 p.
Has a brighter ring on the outside. Center is brighter (than outside the nebula). Without filter, this was very faint, couldn't see the ring.
Very faint, core slightly brighter. Not quite circular. Slightly elongated.
Modestly bright. Circular. Brighter core. Slightly mottled; uneven texture.
Very faint. Large and diffuse.

See 4 spots. The two near the west have penumbras. Largest spot has two components and large penumbra. Spot near the E seems to have some whiter lines/ridges encircling it. These are the largest sunspots I've seen -- have been at solar minimum, and this is the largest sunspot for 3 years!
