Primary A is quite bright white. B is brown-orange and dim. C is very faint, but seen with averted vision.
A, B very close; almost touching. A slightly brighter. C is farther and much dimmer. Nice triple.
8 stars. Makes a nice asterism. Near Pi-Ari. Est class III 2 p.
Wide split, medium bright stars. Should be able to split with a much smaller scope. All stars white.
Surprisingly dim -- found out that the secondary has started dewing up! Fairly wide split. All stars white. A brightest, BC and D just a little dimmer.
Cluster is bounded by a bright pentagon. Other stars faint to very faint. Est class II 3 p.
Very small and faint. Around a bright mag 6.8 double star. Only a few stars clearly seen, main fainter as a slight speckling with averted vision. Est class I 1 m.
Bright, spread out cluster. Marked star is orange. :) Est class II 3 m.
Medium-dim cluster, but seems fairly concentrated. Brightest stars form a jellyfish. Est class III 2 p.
Jupiter - just a white dot. All moons nicely positions as a pinpricks of light. Saturn - can see distinct circle of the planet, and ring structure.
Round, faint, but has a bright core. :) Bright star is Mirach.
Very faint. Circular. Mottled texture. Core brighter.
Extremely faint; only visible occasionally with averted vision. Faint nebulosity around 3 stars.
Faint, except for a few brighter stars. Sparse, strong central concentration. Est class I 3 p.
Can see two bands on Jupiter. Saturn: can see the rings in front and the shadow on the E side.
Bright core, almost stellar. Fades off in a 5:1 aspect ratio. M 32 is starlike but has slight nebulosity.
Small, slightly nebulous. With averted vision, see 3-4 star in a line through the center.
Jupiter - can see one band, hints of a second. Saturn - see rings distinct, but no detail. Jupiter is much brighter than Saturn.
Small blur. Fairly bright. Center is a little brighter.

Easy to locate with a smiley and triangle asterisms. M 38: Bright, center is somewhat concentrated. Hints of stars look like a faint globular. M 36: faint, diffuse, larger, less concentrated. Can only see with averted vision.
Small, bright. Next to M 36. Concentrated, lots of stars, medium variability. Est class I 2 r.
Bright and glittery. Stars white. See about 35 stars in the cluster.
Rough, generally lighter than nearby Mare Crisium and Mare Tranquilitatis.
Bright nebulosity around (apparently) 2 stars; N one is the Trapezium, other is sigma 2 Ori.  Fun region of the sky!
Large, easy to find. Has a mountain with two peaks in the middle. Flat base and rocky outside.
Edges of crater have some sharp peaks following the circle around.  Center has a nice bowl shaped crater with raised sides. Rimae visible.
Mars: very bright, peach color. Resolved as a very small disc. Uranus: starlike, slight blue tint.

Eratosthenes: flat floor, triangular shaped mountain in the middle. Lots of ridges on crater walls. Stadius: Just the rim of the crater is visible. Florr is flat, see some lunar rays from copernicus. A few small craterlets inside, as well as a long chain outside.
Quite faint, just barely lighter than the sky. Next to a row of 3 stars (2 in view). Est class IX.
Has a snake of 6-7 stars, then a mist of fainter ones. Generally resolve with averted vision, though too hard to draw accurately. Est class II 2 m.
Quite faint. No stars resolved, just a slightly lighter patch. Near M 35. Est class II 1 r.
Small, modestly bright. Halfway between two mag 9 stars.  About 20 stars. Est class II 3 p.
About 10 modestly faint stars, and a cluster of much fainter ones (occasionally glimpsed with averted vision). Est class I 2 p.
Dim, spread out, sparse. About 30-40 stars. Est class II 2 p.
See 4 internal craterlets. Flat base, wide hilly, rough edges. Near Clavius.
Right next to Theophilus and Cyrilius. Floor looks pockmarked towards the E side.
Very bright star in the center. Roughtly triangular shaped. :) Est class II 3 p.
Bright, small cluster. About 12 stars. Est class II 2 p.
4036: Modestly bright, elongated. Core is almost stellar. 4041: very faint, diffuse, round. One see occasionally.
Very small. Relatively bright core.
3982: very faint. round. Core is slightly brighter. 3998: very small, almost stellar. (Mistook for a star at first, but is slightly fuzzy.)
Appears as very faint nebulosity around a star.
Bright and obvious. See a pythagorean theorem diagram in the pattern of stars. Lots of fainter stars in the view not drawn.
M46: very faint; slightly lighter patch. M47: Appears as nebulosity around 3-4 stars in the handle of a hockey stick. Bright.
Round fuzzy patch, slightly speckly with stars.
Large, bright circular haze, as of a rich cluster. 3 brighter stars. Marked star, eta Gem, is pale orange.
Moderately faint, sparkly-fuzzy patch. Brighter in the center. Fairly large.
M81: Dim, elongated, has brighter core. M82: small, thin, dim. Make a triangle with two nearby stars.
Bright and small. Core is starlike.
Very faint lighter patch. Core is slightly brighter. Slightly eccentric.
Very bright core, starlike. Mottled texture, suspect two arms. [no, is elliptical]
Bright and concentrated. Almost looks like a class V globular. Bright star is yellow.
Very faint lighter patch. Center noticably brighter. Slightly eccentric.
Very faint, only seen with averted vision. Core not very bright. Seems mottled.
Small, circular. Nearly stellar core. Pretty bright.
Brighter core. Speckled. Generally rather dim. Circular.
Small. Brighter core. Like a class V glob. Easily seen. Right next to a star.
Small. Stellar core. Fairly bright. Near M 106.
Round. Stellar core. Pretty bright.
Faint. Core not very bright. Slightly oval. Appears as a slightly lighter fuzzy patch.
Core is brighter. Rest is pretty dim. Perhaps a spiral galaxy? [yes!] Has some variation in texture.
Very faint, rich. Concentrated a little towards the center. Slightly parkly appearance, but stars are too faint and numerous to resolve. Est class II 2 r.
Dim. Elongated. Core is somewhat brighter, occasionally appears as a fuzzy star with averted vision.
Small, dim. requires averted vision to see. Core a bit brighter.
Extremely faint. Round. Core not brighter.
Small, bright stellar core. Elongated.
Appears as nebulosity around a star.
4490: Bright, elongated, big. Core is brighter, sometimes seems to have two brighter patches. 4485: Very dim. Small, round. Only see occasionally with averted vision.
Small, round, very faint. Core slightly brighter.
Open cluster. See about 20 stars, some only intermittently. Slight central concentration. Est class II 2 p.
Very pretty - large and bright. Seems like some fractal-like pattern. Est class III 3 p.
Very faint, small. See only about 8 stars distinctly with averted vision. Fainter stars make a general glow. Est class II 2 m.
Bright and diverse. Prominent quadrilateral. Sparse. Est class III 3 p.
Really bright, sparse. Like it! Est class III 2 p.
Very faint. Small core is brighter, slightly elongated.
3227: faint, has a brighter core. Mostly seen with averted vision. Slightly elongated. 3226: Smaller and fainter. Round. See occasionally with averted vision.
3190: Elongated. Brighter core, stellar in the middle. 3193: small, round, bright core. Could not see 3187, which should also be in the FOV.
3686: Small. Quite faint. See occasionally with averted vision. Slightly brighter core. 3684: Small, very faint. See occasionally. Round, slightly brighter core.
Big, faint. See 10-20 stars, slightly concentrated at the center. Est class II 2 p.
Faint and large. Inner core stellar, outer core brighter and round.
Core is medium bright and circular. Outer part is faint and elongated.
Faint. Appears as nebulosity around a star.
Faint. Core slightly brighter. Slightly oval-shaped.
Dim. Core is brighter, almost stellar.
Large, faint oval patch. Core slightly brighter.
A: bright, has a slight yellow tint. B: orangy brown color. C: dim, white
A,D both bright white. Wide split even at low power. C: only seen with averted vision; faint. D: very faint, only see occasionally.
All stars white. A, D both very bright. B is dim but easy with direct vision. E is only visible with averted vision.
Pretty triple. :) Resolvable under low power (40x). All stars white, A med bright, B dim, C slightly dimmer.
A, B both very bright, white. A slightly brighter. C, D just white points. :)
All stars white. Easily split. Nice triple. A a little brighter. B, C very similar brightness.
Inside OCl NGC 2232. Primary very bright. B, C similar magnitude, dimmer.
A is brighter, B, C pretty faint, especially B. Close but nicely separated.

Part of M44! Always suspected lots of double stars here. Eng 37: order of brightness is A, B, D, C. S 571: Nice tight triple. Stars have similar brightness. A has a close companion requiring more magnification.
A, B are fairly close; didn't notice this was a double star until I looked closely. All stars are roughtly equal brightness; all white.
Cool asterism; a double at the center of 3 corners of a square. C and D rather faint; A and B pretty bright. :)
AB is bright and yellow. C is cleanly split, and appears yellow-white. D is dimmer.
Primary white, secondary seems orangish,  Saw this through a tree.
A very bright. B very dim, only see occasionally. C dim but easy with direct vision.
Nice little pattern of stars. Y is slightly yellow. A is maybe 1 mag brighter than B. C is very faint, only seen with averted vision.
Appears almost stellar with direct vision. With averted vision, appears as a small fuzzy patch with a bright core.
Very faint, only visible with averted vision. Core not very bright, maybe class VIII.
Stars here are faint, barely seen without averted vision.  3953 is a faint oval, more concentrated at the center. Best seen when moving the scope.
Right at zenith -- very hard to find!  Very faint, barely lighter than the sky. Large, uniform brightness.
Small, fairly bright; nearly stellar core.

Very faint. Had to close my eyes for a minute to be dark adapted enough to see. 4656 elongated; brighter core. 4657 only the core visible, and appears somewhat joined to 4656.  Near NGC 4631 (the Whale).
Dim, but bright core. Elongated, small.
Very faint, elusive; roundish. Core slightly brighter.
Very faint, dim. Med size, oval shaped. Almost appears sparkly/mottled
Small, elongated. Bright core
Dim, but brighter core. Roundish. Mottled texture. Core looks brighter vertically. A bar? [no]
Very faint, difficult. Core slightly brighter. Oval shaped. Only see occasionally.
Fairly bright. Bright core, elongated. Near a faint star.
4473: Bright, core is quite bright, stellar. Oval.  4477: Dimmer, very concentrated stellar core. Elongated a little.
Quite bright. Round, fuzzy. Core is brighter.
M 85: super big and bright. Bright core.  Looks grainy.  4394: small, faint, round. Stellar core.
Dim, though clearly seen with averted vision. Oval. Core is brighter.
Faint, small, elongated. Brighter core. Requires averted vision; only see occasionally.
Dim, elongated. Brighter core, almost stellar. Appears sparkly.
Round. Bright core. Appears elliptical. Easy to see with averted vision.
Very faint; elusive. Elongated. Core only slightly brighter. Slightly sparkly
Bright. Round core is concentrated. Small. [In fact, only seeing the bright core here; galaxy is larger.]
Faint, round. Core somewhat brighter. Appears stellar with averted vision.
Bright core. Can see with direct vision. Mottled, circular, like a faint globular.
Two bright stars in the center of a triangle. Primary and secondary similar brightness; see fair amount of turbulence about them.
Primary is bright, with a yellow tint. Secondary maybe has a faint hint of red. Nice line of 3 stars. :)
Very faint, diffuse, flat.
Brighter core, round. Outer part oval shaped. Mottled texture. Like to check this in darker skies.
Very bright core, starlike. Easy to see. Generally round, but near the core shape seems irregular.
Faint, elongated. Between two stars.
Faint. Elongated. Dim core. Elusive
4281: small, somewhat bright. Stellar core. Circular. 4273: very faint. Core diffuse. Oval.
Faint, small, bright core. Looks like a star with direct vision, but see some fuzziness with averted vision. Bright star is Cor Caroli
Very faint, elusive. Only see occasionally. Elongated in N/S direction. Core slightly brighter.
Very faint, small round, flat gray patch. Only seen with averted vision about 30% of the time.
Prom Agarum looks rough and rocky at the top, casts stark shadows down to Mare Crisium, which appears smooth and gray. Many dorsae are clear as raised ridges
Gray interior. Irregular rocky sides. Par bodering Lame has a double stepped wall. See some internal craterlets as dark spots
Rather bright. Brighter core, though not stellar. Rather like a faint class III globular.
Faint, but not hard with averted vision. Core is brighter, and sparkly. Core is circular, bu thints that galaxy is elongated. Suspect spiral?
4550: small, dim, elongated. Stellar core. M 89: quite bright. Core is bright and stellar. Circular
Dim, but grighter circular core. Outer part elongated. Mottled texture. Spiral?
Large, elongated, very faint. Core not concentrated much. I suspect I'm partially looking through a roof, so using less than full aperture.
Very faint. Appears as slight nebulosity around a star, slightly offset.
Very bright concentrated core. Sparkly outer part, a bit amorphous. Spiral?
Fuzzy and round. Bright core. Overlaps a star. :)
Somewhat faint, bright stellar core. Core is round, but galaxy is oval-shaped.
Looks stellar with direct vision. With averted vision, see some mottled nebulosity. Oval shape.
Very small, elongated. Brighter core, though not stellar.
Small. Elongated. Bright, concentrated core. Though overall faint; best seen with averted vision.
Nice equally-spaced triple! :) B appears orangish, A slightly yellow, C a little bluish.  A brightest, then C, then B.
Drawn slightly enlarged.  A, B have equal brightness. Both yellow. C is dim and white.
Very small, bright. Core is starlike. Looks slightly elongated.
Aristoteles: large. Flat basin. Rocky, uneven walls. One side of the wall very bright white. Mitchell: smaller, flat. Seems to have a bump in the middle.
A brightest, C nearly as bright, and B dimmer, sometimes appears slightly reddish.
A, B have nearly equal brightness nd are wide enough to drive a proverbial truck through. C not too much dimmer.
Nice wide triangle; split in finder. A is bright; light gold color. B a little yellowish as well. C a magnitude dimmer.
A, B brighter and fairly close, but cleanly and easily split. C is dimmer, and D is very faint; can only see occasionally.  Saw a bright meteor pass through the field of view.
AB - unable to split. Cann see some noisy Airy rings faintly. C is maybe 0.7 magnitude dimmer. D is very faint, but clear with averted vision.
A is very bright; pale yellow. C,D are white, similar magnitudes. B is very faint, need averted vision.
Part of a larger group of stars. ABC all pretty bright and easily split. Pretty! :)
Great asterism/multiple stars. Near M104. :) A,B,E,F are bright, D dimmer, and C is faint. E is slightly yellow.
Very bright, wide triple. Could likely see in the finderscope if sky were slightly darker. All stars white.
Primary, secondary nearly equally bright. C is dimmer.
5982: Starlike core, rest very dim. Slightly sparkly. Oval shaped. 5985: very dim, only see occasionally. Small faint, roundish core.
Very faint, long and thin. :) Most stars in FOV are pretty faint too; maybe mag 12.
Stellar core, core is modestly bright. Mottled appearance.
Dim. Brighter, nearly stellar core. Speckled appearance. Near a very faint [mag 13.7] star.
5363 is very bright, small, round. Stellar core. 5364 is extremely faint; only see occasionally as a slightly lighter patch.
Small. Stellar core. Looks like a fuzzy star.
Oval. Brighter core. Outer part dim but mottled. Hints of spiral arms? [No, is elliptical.]
Diffuse and faint; just a light patch. Center slightly brighter.
Faint, small. No stars resolved. Est class IV
Primary white. Secondary slightly orange brown. Other stars need averted vision to see.
Extremely faint. Only see occasionally. Elongated. Core not concentrated.
Extremely faint. See 50% of the time. Large, diffuse. Est class X.
Small. Faint (averted vision only). Concentrated center. No stars resolved. Est class V.

Very faint, lighter fuzzy patch; flat. No central star visible. Only seen with averted vision. * No filter: invisible. * UHC filter: faint gray patch. * OIII filter: like UHC but everything darker and dimmer.  At higher mag (171x + UHC) is larger, but harder to distinguish from the background.

No filter: central star visible with averted vision, nothing else seen.  UHC filter: hints of nebulosity around the CS. CS is very faint (averted vision only). OIII filter: nothing visible.  Also tried 12mm + UHC; better framing with other field stars, but can't see nebula, and CS barely visible.
A is bright white. B is dim, barely visible with direct vision, though bright with averted vision. C is similar to B.
A, B similar magnitudes, though A is slightly brighter. Close, though nicely split at 140x. C is slightly dimmer. :)
Bright, wide triple. Nicely split at 28mm. Very near zenith right now.
Wide triple. Stars a little dim, but are all very similar magnitude.
Very nice, like a small star cluster. :)  C quite bright. A, B close, B rather dim. E, F med bright, G also very faint. Love it!
No filter: CS faint with averted vision. UHC filter: CS fainter. OIII filter: nothing visible. With 8mm + UHC, see faint light area around CS. Confirms observation from yesterday.
Small, faint. stellar core. Elongated. Averted vision required.
Very near M 13. Faint, small, brighter core. Oval shaped.
Flat base. Sharp black shadows. Small hill in the center. Rough outside the crater.

Mars: bright orange, barely resolvable as a disc. Moon. Lots of sharp small craters on the SW side, some detail on the dark side visible at this magnification; see Aristarchus (light) and Grimaldi (dark).  Very cool and unplanned.
A slightly brighter than B. C is much dimmer, best seen with averted vision.
A, B very tight. B is maybe two magnitudes dimmer than A. A little tricky. D is much dimmer, best seen with averted vision. Can't detect C component; should be above B and very faint.
Very bright, easy to see. Est class VIII.
Two small sunspots. Larger one a little elongated; smaller is just touching the larger.  At higher mag (50x), can see 3 more nearby spots in a triangle.

No filter: bright white spot, slightly fuzzy edges. Easily seen with direct vision. No CS visible. UHC filter: still bright, seems to have a larger faint halo, and is no longer circular. OIII: dimmer, view more similar to no filter. Increasing mag to 167x gives slightly larger cleaner view with UHC.
No filter: looks like a bright star, direct vision. With UHC: appears brighter than the other stars, more of a bright disc with soft edges. No CS visible.
A, B bright, wide split, visible at low power. A has a slightly yellow tint, B slightly blusih. C is rather faint.
[Attempted] Not detected. Should be at marked location, right near the star. UHC filter didn't help.
Beta-Oph just outside the FOV to the W. Very bright, loose, sparse wide cluster. Nicely framed here. Stars in the center form a sideways 8. Est class II 2 m.
One bigger spot with a very faint one next to ine. Another smaller one on the other side.
Two spots. One near the edge is darker; the one closer to the center is gray.
Spot a little elongated, curved. At higher mag, resolves into 3 spots.
Two spots near the center.
One spot near the E side. Under higher mag can see it has a prenumbra.
Spot is very dar, prenumbray faintly visible.
Arago not quite circular- has a little circular cutout. I thas 3 smallmountains inside. Alpha and beta are smooth, roundish hills.

At 8mm, seen without filter as an irregular nebulosity around a star. With UHC is brighter patch around a star, elongated. OIII - small bright oval, nothing resolved. Higher power too dimm to see much. Best seen with averted vision; direct vision only see hints (with UHC). Also put in a neutral denisty filter by mistake. Seen only as a faint blur. :)
Somewhat dim, diffuse, though bright spot at core. No stars resolved. Est class III.
One spot, easy to see prenumbra.
Big. Flat bottom, darker gray interior. Mostly encircled with light rough area. Nearby small craterlet with shar contrasty walls.
A looks bluish, B reddish. Very close, not cleanly separated. C, D bright wide split, can easily seen in low pwer eyepiece (40x). Great multiple star!
A, B quite bright. C is faint, only seen with averted vision.
Wide enough to be split at 40x, but C was too dim to see. A is slightly golden, B, C white. C is faint but still seen with direct vision.
Right next to M 107. A bright, C bright, B dim, D very faint, only averted vision.
Small spot with clear prenumbra. Round.
See one sunspot and a thin fractal line on the opposite side (rather faint, white). Also some white lines encircling the spot. [Called faculae.]

Mare Marginis (Sea of the edge) appears as a darker line, near, but not touching the edge of the moon. Same brightness as Mare Crisium. Mare Smythii (Smyth's Sea) thin; has a darker patch, rest lighter than Mare Marginis. Langrangeneus - soft whiteer area, white dot in the very center. Mare Australae (Southern Sea): large, uneven shape, wider near the souther side. Separated from the edge of the moon. Gray interior. Proculs: is bright white, with contrasty lunar rays. Golclenius is a bright white ring with gray interior. Mare Humboltatum (Sea of Humboltatum) has somewhat of a D shape. Mare Undarum (Sea of Waves): patchy, darker areas generally the shape of an epsilon.
Two small spots seen. At higher powers, resolve to 4.

UHC: bright, round, like a slightly defocused star. Direct vision, no CS seen. With no filter: maybe invisible? According to the star atlas, there's a star, fainter than A, just next ot the PLN which is now visible. With UHC filter, seems this star is obscured.

No filter: seen with averted vision as a faint small round patch, concentrated in the middle. No CS. UHC: similar but a bit mor eobvious, visible with direct vision. OIII: ball shape is more clear, but everything is rather dim.
No filter: very faint, barely seen with averted vision; starlike. UHC: more obvious, still starly with averted vision.
No filter: starlike, direct vision. UHC: much brighter (relatively); appears brighter than star B, especially with averted vision. OIII: dim, hard to see.
3 spots. Prenumbra on largest one.
Very sparse OC. Grid-like spacing of stars. See 11-12 stars. Est class III 3 p.

Can't see without a filter. With UHC, occasionally see a hint of a gray patch with averted vision. No CS. Increasing mag to 173x helps a little; can see more often, though still very faint. OIII filter: can't see anything.
One big, dark spot, with prominent prenumbra and tendris coming off! Also 2 more faint spots.
Very sprase OC. 5 prominent stars in the shape of a trapezoid. Est class II 3 p.
Loose, poor cluster. Somewhat faint. Stars appear in several chains. Est class I 1 p.
Within M8 (which shines though the light pollution with an OII filter, but not shown here). Very bright, open. Very nice! Maybe 30 stars. Est class II 3 p.
Sparse open cluster, large variability in magnitudes. 3 bright stars in a triangle and another 3 as part of a chain. Est class III 3 p.
Cassini band clear. Can see a large band near the equator, slightly brownish, and the polar area slightly blue.
